You can use [substr][1] to remove the first `(&quot;` and `&quot;)` and then use explode:

    $string = &#39;(&quot;one&quot;,&quot;two&quot;,&quot;three,subthree&quot;,&quot;four&quot;)&#39;;
    $s = substr($string,2,-2); 
    // now $s is: one&quot;,&quot;two&quot;,&quot;three,subthree&quot;,&quot;four
    print_r(explode(&#39;&quot;,&quot;&#39;, $s));

Which outputs:

    (
        [0] =&gt; one
        [1] =&gt; two
        [2] =&gt; three,subthree
        [3] =&gt; four
    )

Live example: [3v4l][2]


  [1]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.substr.php
  [2]: https://3v4l.org/i7BUX

You can convert the string to JSON string and then decode like this

    $string = &#39;(&quot;one&quot;,&quot;two&quot;,&quot;three,subthree&quot;,&quot;four&quot;)&#39;;
    $string = str_replace([&#39;(&#39;, &#39;)&#39;], [&#39;[&#39;, &#39;]&#39;], $string);

    $array = json_decode($string, true);
    print_r($array);

Working [**demo**][1].


----------


Edit:
=====

If you have possibilities to have brackets [`( or )`] in string, you can trim by brackets [`( or )`] and explode by the delimiter `&quot;,&quot;`. Example:

    $string = &#39;(&quot;one&quot;,&quot;two&quot;,&quot;three,subthree&quot;,&quot;four&quot;)&#39;;
    $string = trim($string, &#39; ()&#39;);

    $array = explode(&#39;&quot;,&quot;&#39;, $string);
    print_r($array);


----------


Another way is to use `preg_match_all()` by the patter `~&quot;([^&quot;])+&quot;~`

    $string = &#39;(&quot;one&quot;,&quot;two&quot;,&quot;three,subthree&quot;,&quot;four&quot;)&#39;;
    preg_match_all(&#39;~&quot;([^&quot;]+)&quot;~&#39;, $string, $array);
    print_r($array[0]);

**[Regex][2] explanation:**

 - `&quot;` matches a double quote
 - `([^&quot;]+)` capturing group
 - `[^&quot;]` any characters except double quote
 - `+` one or more occurrence
 - `&quot;` matches a double quote


  [1]: https://3v4l.org/Rs0EU
  [2]: https://regex101.com/r/ih4vAq/2

Here&#39;s a shorter version to do that:

    $string = &#39;(&quot;one&quot;, &quot;two,three&quot;)&#39;;

    preg_match_all(&#39;/&quot;([^&quot;]+)&quot;/&#39;, $string, $string);

    echo &quot;&lt;pre&gt;&quot;;
    var_dump($string[1]);

